BLUETONGUE, SHEEP - TUNISIA: OIE
*************************************
ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Date: 11 Jan 2003
Source:OIE Disease Information [edited]
<http://www.oie.int/eng/info/hebdo/AIS_37.HTM>

Date of previous reported outbreak in Tunisia: September 2000).
Emergency report
Translation of information received on 7 Jan 2003 from Dr Malek Zrelli,
Director General of Veterinary Services, Ministry of Agriculture, Tunis:
Report date: 7 Jan 2003.
Nature of diagnosis: clinical and laboratory.
Date of initial detection of animal health incident: 15 Dec 2002.
Estimated date of first infection: 1 Dec 2002.
Date of confirmation of diagnosis: 6 Jan 2003.
Outbreaks:
Location / No. of outbreaks
Kairwan governorate / 3
Monastir governorate / 1
Description of affected population: unvaccinated animals.
Total number of animals in the outbreaks:
species/ susceptible/ cases/ deaths/ destroyed/ slaughtered
ovi / 465 / 21 / 6 / 0 / 0
Diagnosis:
A. Laboratory where diagnosis was made: Tunisia Veterinary Research Institute.
B. Diagnostic tests used: competitive ELISA(1) (paired serological tests
carried out on the same animals with a 15-day interval).
C. Causal agent: bluetongue virus type 2.
Epidemiology:
A. Source of agent / origin of infection: the disease was diagnosed first
in December 1999(2). Since that date, vaccination is practised annually.
However, it seems that the virus is still circulating in some pockets where
vaccination cover has not reached an adequate level.
B. Mode of spread: vector-transmitted.
Control measures:
In the outbreaks:
- quarantine;
- confinement and treatment of affected animals;
- burying of dead animals;
- insecticide treatment of animals and facilities.
Around the outbreaks:
- surveillance of farms;
- periodical inspections of flocks.
A national vaccination campaign has been initiated and will continue until
April 2003 using an attenuated monovalent type 2 vaccine.
(1) ELISA: enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay.
(2) See Disease Information, 13 (1), 1, dated 7 Jan 2000, and seq.
